The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	New Delhi, May 4 (PTI): The owner of a vehicle is obliged to compensate a road accident victim if the driver does not have a valid licence, a tribunal has ruled.          
	The court directed Sunil Sehgal to pay Rs 8.4 lakh to the family of Delhi contractor Om Parkash Gupta who died after being hit by a motorcycle four years ago. It exempted the insurance company from paying compensation because of breach of contract. The court rejected Sehgals plea that he had sold the vehicle to the driver before the accident occurred.                   
	Mumbai (PTI): Filmmaker Prabodh Mukherji passed away at a private hospital here on Sunday following a cardiac arrest. He was 88.          
	Mukherji, a great-great-uncle of actress Rani Mukherji, had produced films such as the Shammi Kapoor-starrer Junglee, April Fool, Sharmili, Love Marriage and Mr Romeo.                  
	Melbourne (PTI): Indian doctor Mohammed Haneef, wrongly accused of terror links in Australia, will be under 24-hour police surveillance if he returns to that country. Federal police here are continuing their investigation into the case, which has cost taxpayers almost $8 million.                   
	Sagar (PTI): A man trying to burn a body in a home furnace has been arrested in Madhya Pradesh, police said. A foul smell from the house had made neighbours suspicious on Saturday.                  
	Harda (PTI): A teacher was shot dead at his home in Madhya Pradesh, police said. According to his wife, two unknown assailants barged into the house on Friday night and fired three shots at the victims temple, killing him instantly.                  
	 Islamabad (PTI): The film Jannat starring actor Emran Hashmi is set to debut in India and Pakistan simultaneously on May 16. The films premiere in Pakistan will be held in Lahore on May 13 and the cast, including Hashmi, are expected to attend. Jannat is said to be a take on late Pakistan cricket coach Bob Woolmers life.                                                                                                                         
